{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487265","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487265"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:03:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:03:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"303"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"303","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/303"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.15,0.36,0.02,0.43]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"303"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111322"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"303","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/303"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"303"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93450"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"121"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14202"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14203"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111322","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111322"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old migrant from Thailand presents with a two month history of intermittent painless passage of blood in his urine. The bleeding may occur at any time during micturition. He does not have any other urinary symptoms and is otherwise in good health. The physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Staghorn calculus","Urinary tract tuberculosis","Schistosomiasis","Benign prostatic hyperplasia","Renal cell carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIf the patient had originated from a region in which\u00a0\u003Cem\u003ESchistosoma haematobium\u003C/em\u003E\u00a0was endemic (Africa or the Middle East), then this could be the cause of the patient\u0027s symptoms.\u00a0Urinary tract tuberculosis may cause haematuria but is most commonly associated with urinary frequency and dysuria. It would be uncommon for a staghorn calculus to cause only painless haematuria for two months, as these stones are strongly associated with flank pain and an increased risk of infection.\u00a0It would also be very uncommon for benign prostatic hyperplasia to present with painless haematuria without obstructive or irritative symptoms. The commonest mode of \u0027presentation\u0027 of \u003Cstrong\u003Erenal cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is an incidental finding on imaging (usually CT or ultrasound). However, painless haematuria still remains an important symptom in which renal tract malignancy must be considered. Other possible sites of urinary tract malignancy, particularly the bladder, should also be considered.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most cases of renal cell carcinoma now come to light as incidental radiological findings."],"references":["Yeoh, M, Lai, N, Anderson, D \u0026 Appadurai, V 2013, \u0027Macroscopic haematuria A urological approach\u0027, Australian Family Physician, vol. 42, 3/01, pp. 123-126.","Peterson LM, Reed HS. Hematuria. Prim Care. 2019; 46:265-73."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93450"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"303"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93450"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-12T14:44:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-12T14:44:32+09:30"},"re